data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3+ supports **value tuples** with `DynamicData`, eliminating the `object[]` boxing and giving you compile-time type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>`
- Array literals `["x", true]` → tuple literals `("x", true)`
- The test method signature stays the same — MSTest destructures the tuple into parameters automatically

This catches type mismatches at compile time rather than at test runtime. Requires **MSTest 3.3+**.
